segments.text: Okay.
I was just saying, did we see any basic changes or anything like that?
No, like I said, we're pretty well on an equal scholastic level, and those things have sort of been weeded out of our inputs.
Now, we do have one basic problem around here.
What's that?
And that's Aggies and T-Cyps.
Aggies are definitely inferior, according to TCIP's.
Are the majority of NASA employees here in the military, or are they civilian?
They're all civilian.
Has that changed since NASA first began in the past?
It seemed like all the astronauts were mainly in the military, and all you ever saw were people with the crew cuts and everything.
Has that changed?
Must be talking about Gene Kranz.
Let me tell you first that I've always had military detailees working for me.
They were in the PASS programs for many, many years.
And there was, as far as I know, in terms of pay, they were paid by the military, but it was here for training to learn orbital mechanics and different
flight mechanic skills and how you actually operate in space.
And they used, they donated time, they donated time to the individual, and we went through a training process with them.
And of course, we were able to use them in a productive manner.
As we moved in more into the military, also getting more, being more dependent on the orbiter as a launch vehicle, they have more people here.
They've elected

right now in order to save money and instead of having their own launch facility and duplication of control facilities, et cetera, to co-locate here with us and do all the operations out of the control center, which makes a lot of sense because it does save a lot of taxpayer dollars.
And instead of going over and duplicating the whole operation, that you only use those parts that you need.
So in that case, there is a more than military
they're only working on their pangolins, on their flights.
Is there any tension between the two groups?
Not as bad as the Angus and the T-6.
No, they're very well accepted in both ways, and they work quite well together.
Since you've been at NASA, what changes have taken place as far as our goals in space?
That's a good question.
I think basically the first emphasis was to, it was a national pride.
There was a lot of things being lost in terms of prestige amongst the other countries around the world.
And actually, the technology is one of the best things we've got to sell to the rest of the world.
And you always got to give a country or any individual,
treat a country the same as you would an individual.
You always gotta set goals and objectives above what one can achieve, or make them high, at least, so he will strive to meet those requirements.
And in the process of doing that, there's a lot of spinoff of good products, and the things that we're enjoying today in the commercial world
is a lot of that is spent on some of the things we paid them, the taxpayer money is paid for the R&D development of it.
And the process of doing all that told the national pride in our, in how we looked, and that's a product, that's one of the best products in terms of engineering skills and products.
One of the best things we can sell to foreign countries, and etc.
That's a big exportable item.
We shifted from really more or less as a nation trying to be number one in space and etc.
to a point of where we're trying to go into more of the commercial world and actually sell time in space, work with other customers.
So it was a shift from a
a national pride type of thing, I think, to now more, hey, I satisfy the customer internationally, et cetera, who wants to fly out in space.
Does that make sense?
Yeah.
Yeah.
So, I mean, we've gone from just wanting to be the first in space, or first to do this, or first to be on the moon in the best, to commercialism.
Yeah, the old commercialism has taken over there now,
that also has money to be made.
It doesn't have to be subsidized by the government.
What do you think Russia's steps will be?
I mean, seeing as how they are a non-capitalistic nation, what will their steps be?
Or where are they, you know, where they're working, what they're working on, what they're trying to accomplish?
I suspect, I think they're trying to, I've heard rumors about having a
getting a larger launch vehicle going to put more weight into space.
I think you'll see them probably moving in the morning to maybe larger space stations.
Well, ours are being used for commercialistic reasons.
What will theirs, what do you think theirs will be used for?
I think they'll obviously be looking at both areas.
There's one definitely militaristic thing that could be used with them.
But also they're interested in doing commercial development of various things, so they'll be doing a lot of experiments and things like that on board, and manufacturing and that sort of stuff.
What are NASA's plans after the show?
After the show?
Well, there's really no such thing as after the show.
If you're at the space station, okay.
The reason I say that, you can look at the, the shuttle's gonna be around for years.
It's gonna be like the original.
It's gonna be like the DC-3s that's been flying now for, what, 40 years.
Commercial air, like 707s, 747s, the planes don't sort of go away.
They just, they keep flying and you get better ones.
I wouldn't be surprised if you don't see the basic orbiter flying for another,
It was designed for 10 years.
It'll probably fly for 20 or 30 years at least.
And of course, we're talking about upgrading it, making it better.
And when we move into the space station, which is what we're doing now, that occupies pretty well for the next 10 years.
And then after that, I think we'll see a man.
There's two moves.
There's one talking about going back to the moon and putting some planetary bases there.
So pretty wild ideas of things we can do on the moon in terms of commercial.

There's a concept that we'll put power generating stations on the lunar surface that would produce, gather the sun's energy and focus it back to the earth and be able to collect it and provide it for commercial use for
I was saying, I've heard of numbers where it would be done as cheap as we can do it now, currently here on the Earth, so then that type of development comes with an endless supply of energy.
We just use the sun's energy reflected from big reflectors on the lunar surface.
And you're talking about, for example there, one concept is you take a bunch of bulldozers up there and you bulldoze this big surface out into reflecting areas.
where it becomes a collector and focuses that energy back to the earth.
There's a lot of different groups pushing different ways.
I suspect we probably see some in-planetary man, in-planetary exploratory activities.
And then also maybe a man permanent presence on the moon.
Back to the question about women and blacks.
the Russians were the first one to put a woman in orbit, and the first to have a co-ed flight.
Why, you know, you said that women were always here employed.
Why do you think it took so long for them to be put into space here in America?
Well, one can go from the point of trying to find somebody who's really qualified to, to stand to the rigors of doing that activity, and that's
That has some semi-merits, might say weak merits probably.
One of the things that preconditioning for the early flights was to have somebody who had had a lot of training in an aircraft business or military realistic type training.
That was a resource that saved a lot of cross training.
And that was a simple resource to draw upon.
And then the other thing is there's a lot of accommodations that would have made it difficult.
It would be a lot more engineering work to have to do to set the accommodations for women as simple as it was for men, like potty accommodations and that sort of stuff.
So, when you're trying to put together a facility,
minimize the complications.
So I think it's one of those just to have the right accommodations and putting it into the design and working with getting qualified people.
Has that taken a lot of adjustment in the shuttle to accommodate it to work?
I don't think so.
I think that accommodations were sort of built in from scratch.
You know, it was sort of built in.

and that's different than having to go back in and redesign, and of course the concept there was that it was actually built into the design, and it's, I think about the original question, one of the problems was that we, these selected, NASA selected to use the military pilots and things as a prime source of
of astronaut candidates.
And... At that time, women weren't in the military?
They weren't in the military, but too early.
I don't think you had too many fighter pilots and that sort of stuff.
And that's basically what they were looking for.
I mean, you could select another group of people as a source of people to pick from.
But they just happened to say, hey, let's go to the military and use them.
So they might have used truck drivers.
Has there been much of an impact here at NASA with women here and blacks?
Has there been any prejudices?
Not really.
No more than, I wouldn't say normal, just everybody really
It's more on a technical level, and everybody respects you from a technical standpoint.
And you usually don't pull a lot of punches.
I have two ladies I'm working with now that seem to be tigers.
They definitely don't pull no punches on us.
In closing, today,
the press came out and said that Soviet leader Konstantin Chernenko died yesterday.
What type of effect would the death of a Soviet leader and the question of who will be appointed next have on anything, you know, as far as our scheduling?
Does that, are we, do we have to reschedule if someone, you know, really non-American or, you know, down on Americans gets appointed?
What does something like that do around here?

I don't think it's gonna, we're pretty well insulated from that right now, since we're not really materialistic, otherwise not involved with the military that much at the center, that I don't see this having a lot to do with how we operate here.
They have a mental impact.
And we're pretty well, I like to say, pretty well insulated from all that activity.
and those type of major decisions.

Now if they come out with, but on the other hand if they come out and made a major statement that he's going to put manned, manned a station on the moon or make a big push for Mars or something like that, do a manned landing on Mars, and that was the national objective of the Russians, obviously those type of decisions would definitely affect us.
Okay, well thank you for your time.
Enjoy it.
Thank you.
